         <abstract>
            <p>Since 1974, several algorithms have been developed that attempt to factor a large number $N$ by doing extensive computations modulo $N$ and occasionally taking GCDs with $N$. These began with Pollard's $p - 1$ and Monte Carlo methods. More recently, Williams published a $p + 1$ method, and Lenstra discovered an elliptic curve method (ECM). We present ways to speed all of these. One improvement uses two tables during the second phases of $p \pm 1$ and ECM, looking for a match. Polynomial preconditioning lets us search a fixed table of size $n$ with $n/2 + o(n)$ multiplications. A parametrization of elliptic curves lets Step 1 of ECM compute the $x$-coordinate of $nP$ from that of $P$ in about $9.3 \log_2 n$ multiplications for arbitrary $P$.</p>
          </abstract>
